{
  "answer": "**No work in the Falsafa corpus matches this description exactly.**\n\nI searched the English translations of all Sanskrit-language works (Aṅgirasa Smṛti, Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Kātyāyana Smṛti, Manu Smṛti, Nārada Smṛti, Parāśara Smṛti, Viṣṇu Smṛti, Vīramitrodaya, Yama Smṛti, and Yājñavalkya Smṛti) using distinctive phrases from the query (e.g., \"sacred fire\", \"abandoned his sacred fire\", \"hair bones corpse\", \"garland corpse\", \"hair of corpse\", \"fanned with hair\", \"smearing ashes\", \"banish Brahmin\", \"king\" \"banish\", \"violates convention\"). No results contained the prescribed punishments or the adjacent verses.\n\nThe closest passage (Bṛhaspati Smṛti 1.19.6, ¶ [p-026685]) describes humiliating a Śūdra boundary-guide by smearing his face with corpse-ash and marking him with animal blood, but it lacks the Brahmin abandoning fire, fumigation with corpse-hair/bones, banishment, nakedness, fanning, or corpse-hair garland—and it is not penitential for a Brahmin.[^1]\n\nNo other penitential (*prāyaścitta*-focused) text prescribes these rituals verbatim or adjacently. The corpus covers standard Smṛti punishments (e.g., fines, banishment for theft/violence, penances for purity violations), but not this sequence.\n\n[^1]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-026685).",
